Vancouver police have issued a Canada-wide arrest warrant for a high-risk sex offender.

Cameron Leon, 22, failed to return to his halfway house Monday night, police said in a media release. He is on statutory release serving a two-year sentence for sexual assault causing bodily harm and assault causing bodily harm.

Leon is Aboriginal, 5'11", 195 pounds with brown eyes and black hair. He wears perscription glasses and has a tattoo of "Leon" on his right hand, as well as wings and a cross on his upper back.

Police said he was last seen wearing a grey "Puma" hoode and carrying a black backpack.

Anyone who sees Leon is asked to stay away and call 911.

status_message:
Vancouver police have issued a Canada-wide warrant for a high-risk sex offender who didn't return to his halfway house on Thursday.

Keith Edward Caouette, 45, is a two-time offender who's served 14 years for kidnapping and sexual assault with a weapon. He left his halfway house around 5:30 p.m. and didn't come back by curfew, police said in a media release.

Caouette is described as Aborginal, 6' tall, 300 pounds, with green eyes and brown hair tied in a ponytail. He has a full sleeve on his left arm, three skulls on his right bicep, and a skull band on his right wrist.

Police said Caouette is a high risk to reoffend violently with a lengthy criminal record. Anyone who sees him is asked to stay away and call 911.

status_message:
On December 6, 1989 a gunman killed 14 women at the Universite du Montreal's Ecole polytechnique. We remember them. 

Top row (from left to right)
Geneviève Bergeron
Hélène Colgan
Nathalie Croteau
Barbara Daigneault
Anne-Marie Edward
Maud Haviernick
Barbara Klucznik-Widajewicz

Bottom row (from left to right)

Maryse Laganière
Maryse Leclair
Anne-Marie Lemay
Sonia Pelletier
Michèle Richard
Annie St-Arneault
Annie Turcotte

status_message:
On this day in 1951, Canadian feminist, social activist, and politician Nellie McClung died in Victoria, B.C. at the age of 77. 

"If I were young again-and I wish I could go back- I would spend my life as a teacher of young children, doing all in my power to give them a vision of the dignity and glory of being builders and planters, makers and menders," she wrote in her autobiography.

McClung dedicated her life to fighting for human rights and is most famous for her work with Canada's women's suffrage movement. In 1914, she held a mock Parliament in Manitoba to lampoon arguments against giving women the right to vote by presenting a satiric case for male suffrage – and it worked.

Two years later, Manitoba became the first Canadian province to give women the vote in 1916. She continued to help fight for women's suffrage and equality in other provinces, and advocated for Aboriginal and Asian women's rights during her career as a politician.

Photo: Library and Archives Canada / Cyril Jessop

status_message:
The Q&A excerpt below is from the Epilogue our free eBook, Contender: The Justin Trudeau Story, which outlines Justin Trudeau's origins and the challenges the Liberal Party faces before the 2015 election. It was written by our bureau chief Althia Raj and published in early March

Q: The Trudeau name, the baggage that you carry.. does it bother you?

Justin Trudeau: It is just a fact of my life, and I wouldn't know what it is to live in a different way ... You look at children of successful parents or powerful parents or famous parents and it seems to be an awful burden for so many of them, the fact is my parents were extraordinarily good at giving their children the tools to handle the extra expectations and pressures.

Having a name and baggage like we do means that we have to work extra hard to justify retroactively the doors that automatically open for us. Because there are some that open but it makes it two or three times harder for us to walk through them with our heads held high, if we are going to do it right.

Q: Do you feel that you are part of a dynasty?

JT: No. I understand the sense of connectedness that people have to my family and the association to Canadian politics but dynasties are about passing on hereditary titles and there was nothing hereditary or inevitable about going into politics or even being successful in politics. The way sons of teachers often end up being teachers and daughters of doctors end up being doctors, and many children of politicians end up in politics as well … it is because the experience you get growing up in a political household. So, no, I think that dynasty is an easy shorthand that allows people to explain what is a much more complex phenomenon which has to do with, all things being equal, you are more likely to pick someone you know for a job opening than someone you don't know for a job opening. But dynasty? Nah.

Get the book (for Apple, Kindle, Kobo, PDF and other formats) here: http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/03/05/contender-justin-trudeau-ebook-download_n_2784222.html
link_name: Timeline Photos
